'''John J. Renton''' is a professor of [[geology]] at [[West Virginia University]], known for the quality of the teaching in his introductory geology courses<ref>{{citation|title=They're rare, but a few college classes are so inspiring that students consider them must-takes|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/lifestyle/20031221courses1221fnp1.asp|journal=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=December 21, 2003|first=Bill|last=Schackner}}.</ref> and in the video version of the course, Nature of Earth.<ref name=gates/>  In 2002, he was named an Eberly Family Professor for Distinguished Teaching, one of only four at the University.<ref name="wvu">{{cite web|url=http://wvutoday.wvu.edu/news/page/1006/|title=Renton named Eberly Family Distinguished Professor at WVU|date=June 22, 2002|publisher=West Virginia University|accessdate=2009-04-15}}</ref>

==Education==
Renton earned a B.S. from [[Waynesburg College]] in 1956, and his M.S. and Ph.D. from West Virginia University in 1959 and 1963 respectively.<ref>{{citation|title=Slide, Video and CD Program Library|format=review of ''Nature of Earth''|first=Bill|last=Gissler|journal=CFMS Newsletter|volume=XLIV|issue=4|date=April 2007|url=http://www.cfmsinc.org/newsletter/news2007/004apr07/newsapr07.htm}}.</ref>

==Academic career==
He has taught at the university since 1965.<ref name=wvu/>  His research specializations are coal geology and geochemistry.<ref>[http://www.geo.wvu.edu/people/faculty WVU Geology faculty listing].</ref>

==Nature of Earth==
Renton has created a 36 part lecture series on DVD called Nature of Earth.  [[Bill Gates]] has this program as example of the sorts of educational innovation that the [[Gates Foundation]] intends to support, calling the course "phenomenal".<ref name=gates>{{citation|title=Bill and Melinda Gates go back to school|first=Claudia|last=Wallis|date=November 26, 2008|journal=[[CNN Money]]|url=http://money.cnn.com/2008/11/25/magazines/fortune/GatesFoundation_Wallis.fortune/}}.</ref>

